<emphasis id="B92AFD3EFFE6683B459A342DBB40FECD" bold="true" box="[199,315,294,320]" pageId="19" pageNumber="302">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C5E5AAFFFE6683B441F342DB835FECD" baseAuthorityName="Neboiss" baseAuthorityYear="1994" box="[322,590,294,320]" class="Insecta" family="Polycentropodidae" genus="Nyctiophylax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="302" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spiculatus">
<emphasis id="B92AFD3EFFE6683B441F342DB835FECD" box="[322,590,294,320]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="302">Nyctiophylax spiculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally recorded from only one NT site (Howard Springs) and many sites in northern WA (both the Kimberley and Pilbara Regions) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF5CDDFFE6683B46DC3441BE58FEE9" author="Neboiss, A." box="[897,1059,330,356]" pageId="19" pageNumber="302" pagination="191 - 205" refId="ref15513" refString="Neboiss, A. (1994) A review of the genus Paranyctiophylax Tsuda from Sulawesi, Papua New Guinea and northern Australia (Trichoptera: Polycentropodidae). Memoirs of the Museum of Victoria, 54, 191 - 205. https: // doi. org / 10.24199 / j. mmv. 1994.54.09" type="journal article" year="1994">Neboiss 1994</bibRefCitation>
). The species is recorded from a further seven sites in the NT.
</paragraph>
